    <scopecontent id="aspace_f59c2b7258071ba4a0f312b4a5568381">
      <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
      <p>Leaflets, position papers, handwritten and typewritten notes (written by Coopersmith, some in shorthand, some on the back of leaflets or as marginalia), mailing lists, armbands, stickers, pamphlets, newspapers, clippings and posters mostly pertaining to student radicalism in the United States in the late 1960s and early 1970s--mainly, but not only at New York University, and mainly, but not only to Students for a Democratic Society (SDS). There is also a small amount of conservative and Young Republican literature. Also included are research files on subjects of interest to Coopersmith, such as the CIA, Cuba, and syndicalism. The posters were printed during the New York University student strike of May 1970 on the University's own printing presses, when students seized control of the University's print shop during their nearly two-week occupation of Kimball Hall, the university building that housed the presses. Both students and members of off-campus organizations (such as the Black Panthers and Young Lords) produced these posters. Subjects include opposition to the war in Vietnam and Cambodia, to imperialism and police brutality, the deaths of student strikers on the campuses of Kent State and Jackson State that month, and the imposition of an injunction against the occupation of Kimball Hall (one poster urging NYU students to join their "injunction party" and "make revolutionary love in the streets"). One of the posters, satirically describing the signers of the Declaration of Independence as "long-haired radicals," was designed and printed by Coopersmith herself.</p>
    </scopecontent>
